Description . Size small, 1.8 –5.0. Carapace ovoid, with inconspicuous thoracic fovea in males, absent in females (
Fig. 9 A‒B
), posterior border truncate (
Figs 13 A
,
14 B
). Eight subequal eyes grouped on a distinct tubercle. Clypeus almost horizontal (
Fig. 9 A
). Chelicerae robust, fused at base, with distal promarginal lamina, and serrula with short teeth (
Fig. 15 A‒D
). Sternum without sigilla, fused at labium. Spines absent on legs. Female pedipalpal tarsus hirsute, no spines, claw with 10–11 teeth. Leg I–IV with many irregularly distributed sensilla and featherlike setae (
Fig. 15 D‒G
) as well as chemosensitive setae (
Figs 10 C
,
15 D
). Leg II of male unmodified. Calamistrum short, triseriate, comprising elongate and comb-like setae (
Figs 10 E‒F
,
15 H
). Three pectinate claws, the paired claws with 7–9 teeth and the unpaired claw with 3–4 teeth (
Fig. 10 A‒D
). Tarsal organ capsulated, slightly elevated and smooth (
Fig. 15 E‒F
) sometimes paired with a sensill (
Fig. 15 G
). Male palpal femur long, almost one third larger than tibia (
Fig. 9 C‒D
), with a ventral median group of erect setae. Tibia thick, longer than the patella, hirsute, no spines, lyriform organs subdistal (
Fig. 19 G‒H
) and with a retrolateral distal projection with strong spines that have a blunt distal area (
Figs 9 C
,
11 A, D‒E
,
16 B, G
). Cymbium long, narrow, very slender, distally tapering, reaching almost to the embolus tip (
Fig. 16 A‒F
), with at least one small sensill, scattered chemosensitive setae (
Fig. 11 G
), one smooth seta on the prolateral border (
Fig. 11 H
) and feathery setae that are elongated at the tip (
Fig. 16 C‒D
). Tegulum pyriform (
Fig. 9 D
). Embolus long, without paraembolic lamina, generally sinuous at tip (
Figs 11 A
,
16 C‒G
). Female genitalia with an elongated uterus externus, sometimes surpassing dorsally the spermathecae (
Fig. 14 E
) or short, but enlarged in some species (
Figs 20 D
; 21 C) and one pair of spermathecae with a narrow and sinuous neck leading to a globose or oval receptaculum (
Figs 9 F
,
14 E
,
20 C
). Abdomen oval and slightly hirsute (
Fig. 9 A‒B
). Cribellum divided (
Figs 10 H
,
12 A
). Spinnerets subterminal. ALS and PMS with rows of large modified setae (
Fig. 12 B
). ALS with one major ampullate gland spigot situated laterally to the piriform gland spigot field (
Fig. 12 C
). PLS with clavate setae, at least two aciniform spigots (
Fig. 12 D
) and at least one paracribellar gland spigot (
Fig. 12 A
). PMS with one paracribellar gland spigot, one minor ampullate gland spigot and a few aciniform gland spigots (
Fig. 12 E‒F
